    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-02-01T10:52:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-02-01T10:52:00-05:00" n="250"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d250">
                <head>250. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d250fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, RG 59, Central Files 1967–69, <gloss target="#t_POL1"
                            >POL</gloss> 33–6 KOR N–US. Secret; Immediate; Nodis; <gloss
                            target="#t_Cactus1">Cactus</gloss>. Repeated to the White House. Drafted
                        by <persName corresp="#p_BSD1">Berger</persName>, cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_RBH1">Read</persName>, and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-02-01T15:52:00+00:00">February 1, 1968,
                        1552Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>108281. 1. We do not know what North Korean Senior Member may propose as terms
                    for release of Pueblo. We guess that it may be signing of receipt similar to
                    helicopter case. On that you have guidance …i.e. that you have no authority to
                    sign statement. You can also say that soon as we have access to the crew, we
                    will make an investigation. And if the facts should prove contrary to our data
                    that the <hi rend="italic">Pueblo</hi> was at all times in international waters,
                    we shall express regrets.</p>
                <p>2. Admiral <persName corresp="#p_SRAJV1">Smith</persName> should keep emphasizing
                    accepted international law and procedures for any warship that infringes
                    territorial waters. We are sending you relevant texts septel to be sure you have
                        them.<note n="2" xml:id="d250fn2">See <ref target="#d251">Document
                        251</ref>. Telegram 108367 to Seoul, February 1, contained detailed
                        information relative to legal issues affecting the seizure of the Pueblo.
                        (National Archives and Records Administration, RG 59, Central Files 1967–69,
                            <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 33–6 KOR N–US)</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0608" n="576" xml:id="pg_576"/>
                <p>3. Should they make bargaining gambits such as exchanging prisoners of war, or
                    ask for reduction of US forces in South Korea, etc. you should listen but say
                    you have no authority to discuss these matters.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
